{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639560"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:06:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:06:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17778"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17778"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.15,0.05,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10492"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74800"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10492"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17778"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60286"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6233"},{"type":"tags","id":"7065"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"},{"type":"tags","id":"9750"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24493"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24499"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74800"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of urinary frequency, hesitancy, poor stream, nocturia, and terminal dribbling. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe also reports a dull pain around the lower part of the right side of his chest, which is not acute. He denies any recent falls or trauma. On further investigation, imaging reveals two lower rib fractures. The patient has no recollection of any incident that could have caused these fractures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a diagnosis of concern?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metastatic prostate cancer","Chronic kidney disease","Benign prostatic hyperplasia","Osteoporosis","Rib contusion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of urinary symptoms and unexplained rib fractures in this patient raises the suspicion of \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic prostate cancer\u003C/strong\u003E. Prostate cancer can metastasise to the bones, leading to pathological fractures without significant trauma. The urinary symptoms such as frequency, hesitancy, and poor stream are indicative of prostate pathology, which could be due to benign prostatic hyperplasia or prostate cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E could cause bone changes due to renal osteodystrophy, but it would not typically present with urinary symptoms as described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenign prostatic hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the urinary symptoms but would not account for the rib fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoporosis\u003C/strong\u003E could lead to fractures with minimal trauma, but it would not explain the urinary symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERib contusion\u003C/strong\u003E would typically be associated with a history of trauma and would not explain the urinary symptoms or the presence of fractures on imaging.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metastatic prostate cancer can present with urinary symptoms and pathological fractures due to bone metastases.","Prostate cancer often metastasises to the bone, leading to fractures without significant trauma.","Urinary symptoms such as frequency, hesitancy, and poor stream can be indicative of prostate pathology."],"references":["Posdzich P, Darr C, Hilser T, Wahl M, Herrmann K, Hadaschik B, Gr\u00fcnwald V. Metastatic Prostate Cancer-A Review of Current Treatment Options and Promising New Approaches. Cancers (Basel). 2023 Jan 11;15(2):461. doi: 10.3390/cancers15020461. PMID: 36672410; PMCID: PMC9856730.","Manna F, Karkampouna S, Zoni E, De Menna M, Hensel J, Thalmann GN, Kruithof-de Julio M. Metastases in Prostate Cancer. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2019 Mar 1;9(3):a033688. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a033688. Erratum in: Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2018 Jul 2;8(7):a035568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a035568. PMID: 29661810; PMCID: PMC6396340.","Posdzich P, Darr C, Hilser T, Wahl M, Herrmann K, Hadaschik B, Gr\u00fcnwald V. Metastatic Prostate Cancer-A Review of Current Treatment Options and Promising New Approaches. Cancers (Basel). 2023 Jan 11;15(2):461. doi: 10.3390/cancers15020461. PMID: 36672410; PMCID: PMC9856730.","Sartor O, de Bono JS. Metastatic Prostate Cancer. N Engl J Med. 2018 Feb 15;378(7):645-657. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra1701695. Epub 2018 Feb 7. PMID: 29412780."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60286"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17778"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60286"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T09:27:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T09:27:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10492"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74800"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attribute